Activities on the Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) yesterday continued to skew downwards following sustained sell-off resulting in the equities market dropping by 0.24 per cent.
The decline was impacted by negative sentiment of investors on blue chip stocks.
Consequently, the All-Share Index shed 136.68 basis points or 0.24 per cent to close at 30,029.15 index points as against 30,099.83 recorded the previous day, while market capitalisation of equities depreciated by N32 billion to close lower at N13.224 trillion from N13.256 trillion.
Meanwhile, a turnover of 242 million shares in 3,183 deals was recorded in the day’s trading.
Banking sub-sector was the most active (measured by turnover volume) with 107.2 million shares exchanged by investors in 589 deals.
Volume in the sub-sector was largely driven by activities in the shares of GTBank Plc and ETI Plc.
Premium sub-sector boosted by the activities in the shares of Zenith Bank and UBA Plc followed with a turnover of 80.7 million shares in 517 deals.
The number of gainers at the close of trading session was 14, while decliners closed at 15.
Further analysis of the day’s trading showed that GSK Plc topped the gainers’ table with 9.15 per cent to close at N8.35 per share, while May and Baker Plc followed with 6.33 per cent to close at N2.35 per share. Mutual Benefits Insurance Plc trailed with a gain of five per cent to close at 29 kobo per share.
On the flip side, C and I Leasing Plc led the losers’ chart with a drop of 9.84 per cent to close at N6.30 per share. NPF Microfinance Bank Plc tailed with a loss of 9.72 per cent to close at N1.30 per share respectively. UAC Property Plc trailed with 8.48 per cent to close at N1.51 per share.